{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is the handoff between file discovery/parsing and the migration execution loop (MOCK-MISS). No real network/OS subprocess behavior is required for this specific ordering check (REAL-INFRA). A unit test of only the sort helper can miss wiring bugs where unsorted files are actually executed.","test_description":"Create a test migrations directory with out-of-order filenames (e.g., 010, 002, 001), run the runner with a test DB adapter and filesystem access, and assert executed migration order is 001 -> 002 -> 010 and recorded versions match that order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior depends on interaction between migration execution and metadata-table read/write across two runs (MOCK-MISS). It does not inherently require subprocess or external API behavior (REAL-INFRA). Pure unit tests can miss state handoff bugs between modules.","test_description":"Run the runner twice against the same test database state and migration files; verify first run executes and records the migration, second run skips execution and leaves side effects unchanged while preserving metadata.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Rollback correctness depends on real PostgreSQL transaction semantics and error handling behavior that mocks can hide (MOCK-HIDE, REAL-INFRA). Also requires verifying stop-on-failure behavior in the same run after a real DB error.","test_description":"Against a real PostgreSQL instance, run migrations where one file performs a write then triggers SQL failure; assert no partial changes from that file persist, later migration files are not executed, and metadata is not advanced past the failing migration.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is inherently cross-process concurrency with shared DB state and lock/uniqueness behavior (REAL-INFRA). Mocked concurrency or single-process simulation can miss real race conditions (MOCK-HIDE).","test_description":"Launch two runner processes concurrently against the same real PostgreSQL database and identical migration set; assert each migration’s side effect appears exactly once and `_migrations` has exactly one row per version with no duplicates.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.95,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the `_migrations` table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is initialization ordering between metadata bootstrap and migration application modules (MOCK-MISS). No LLM or multi-step agentic dependency. Real external API/process is not strictly required for the ordering contract itself.","test_description":"Start from an empty database schema, run the runner once, and assert `_migrations` exists before first migration record/write path is used, and migrations then apply successfully in that same run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
